To integrate the pest and disease component into the database, we need to create a new table for the component in the database. The table should include columns for the following data:

* `id`: unique identifier for each record in the table
* `pest_or_disease`: string value indicating whether the record is for a pest or a disease
* `name`: name of the pest or disease
* `description`: description of the pest or disease
* `symptoms`: common symptoms associated with the pest or disease
* `causes`: common causes of the pest or disease
* `treatments`: common treatments for the pest or disease
* `prevention`: common prevention measures for the pest or disease

We can use SQL to create the table:
```vbnet
CREATE TABLE pest_disease (
  id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY,
  pest_or_disease TEXT NOT NULL,
  name TEXT NOT NULL,
  description TEXT,
  symptoms TEXT,
  causes TEXT,
  treatments TEXT,
  prevention TEXT
);
```
Once the table is created, we can modify the backend code to allow for inserting, updating, and deleting records in the table. We can also modify the frontend UI to allow users to search for pests or diseases and display the relevant information for each record in the table.

For example, the backend code for inserting a new record might look like this:
```javascript
app.post('/pests_diseases', function(req, res) {
  var pest_or_disease = req.body.pest_or_disease;
  var name = req.body.name;
  var description = req.body.description;
  var symptoms = req.body.symptoms;
  var causes = req.body.causes;
  var treatments = req.body.treatments;
  var prevention = req.body.prevention;

  var sql = "INSERT INTO pest_disease (pest_or_disease, name, description, symptoms, causes, treatments, prevention) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?)";
  var params = [pest_or_disease, name, description, symptoms, causes, treatments, prevention];

  db.run(sql, params, function(err) {
    if (err) {
      console.log(err);
      res.status(500).send(err);
    } else {
      res.send("Record inserted");
    }
  });
});
```
This code takes in the data for a new pest or disease record and inserts it into the `pest_disease` table in the database. We can similarly modify the code for updating and deleting records.

For the frontend UI, we can create a search bar that allows users to search for pests or diseases by name. When a user searches for a pest or disease, the app can query the backend to get the relevant information from the `pest_disease` table and display it on the screen. We can also add sorting and filtering options to the UI to make it easier for users to find the information they need.

To integrate alert and notification for the pest and disease control management component in the farm management app, we can use a combination of backend code and frontend UI.

Backend:

1. Create a notification/alerts table in the database to store notifications/alerts data such as title, message, timestamp, and status (read or unread).
2. When a pest or disease is detected, create a new notification in the database with the appropriate data.
3. Add a notification system to the backend to automatically send notifications to registered users when a new notification is created.

Frontend:

1. Add a notification icon/button to the UI.
2. When a user clicks on the notification icon/button, display a list of unread notifications.
3. When a user clicks on a notification, mark it as read and redirect them to the appropriate page (e.g., the pest or disease control management page).

Example code:

Backend (Node.js + Express + PostgreSQL):
```javascript
// Create notifications table
const createNotificationsTable = async () => {
  try {
    await pool.query(`
      CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS notifications (
        id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,
        title TEXT NOT NULL,
        message TEXT NOT NULL,
        timestamp TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
        status VARCHAR(10) NOT NULL
      );
    `);
  } catch (err) {
    console.error(err.message);
  }
};

// Create new notification
const createNotification = async (title, message) => {
  try {
    const queryText = `
      INSERT INTO notifications (title, message, status)
      VALUES ($1, $2, $3)
      RETURNING *
    `;
    const values = [title, message, 'unread'];
    const result = await pool.query(queryText, values);
    return result.rows[0];
  } catch (err) {
    console.error(err.message);
  }
};

// Get unread notifications for a user
const getUnreadNotifications = async (userId) => {
  try {
    const queryText = `
      SELECT *
      FROM notifications
      WHERE status = 'unread'
      ORDER BY timestamp DESC
    `;
    const result = await pool.query(queryText);
    return result.rows;
  } catch (err) {
    console.error(err.message);
  }
};

// Mark notification as read
const markNotificationAsRead = async (notificationId) => {
  try {
    const queryText = `
      UPDATE notifications
      SET status = 'read'
      WHERE id = $1
    `;
    const values = [notificationId];
    await pool.query(queryText, values);
  } catch (err) {
    console.error(err.message);
  }
};
```
Frontend (React):
```javascript
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import axios from 'axios';

const NotificationIcon = () => {
  const [showNotifications, setShowNotifications] = useState(false);
  const [notifications, setNotifications] = useState([]);

  const fetchNotifications = async () => {
    const response = await axios.get('/api/notifications/unread');
    setNotifications(response.data);
  };

  const markNotificationAsRead = async (notificationId) => {
    await axios.patch(`/api/notifications/${notificationId}/read`);
    fetchNotifications();
  };

  useEffect(() => {
    fetchNotifications();
  }, []);

  return (
    <div>
      <button onClick={() => setShowNotifications(!showNotifications)}>
        Notifications ({notifications.length})
      </button>
      {showNotifications && (
        <div>
          {notifications.map((notification) => (
            <div
              key={notification.id}
              onClick={() => markNotificationAsRead(notification.id)}
              style={{
                backgroundColor: notification.status === 'unread' ? 'lightgray' : 'white',
              }}
```
